    "# ⚡ Activation Functions Explorer\n",
    "\n",
    "Welcome to the **Activation Functions Explorer** notebook! This notebook is designed to give you a deep understanding of activation functions, their mathematical behavior, their derivatives, and how they affect training dynamics.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 📓 Table of Contents\n",
    "1. [Theory and Math Recap](#1-Theory-and-Math-Recap)\n",
    "2. [Interactive Implementations](#2-Interactive-Implementations)\n",
    "3. [Visualizing Gradients and Saturation](#3-Visualizing-Gradients-and-Saturation)\n",
    "4. [Exercises & Solutions](#4-Exercises-&-Solutions)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Theory and Math Recap\n",
    "\n",
    "Activation functions introduce **non-linearity** into the network, allowing it to approximate arbitrary functions (Universal Approximation Theorem).\n",
    "\n",
    "### Core Functions:\n",
    "- **Sigmoid**: $\\sigma(z) = \\frac{1}{1 + e^{-z}}$\n",
    "- **Tanh**: $\\tanh(z) = \\frac{e^z - e^{-z}}{e^z + e^{-z}}$\n",
    "- **ReLU**: $f(z) = \\max(0, z)$\n",
    "- **Leaky ReLU**: $f(z) = \\max(\\alpha z, z)$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "def sigmoid(z):\n",
    "    return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-np.clip(z, -500, 500)))\n",
    "\n",
    "def sigmoid_deriv(z):\n",
    "    s = sigmoid(z)\n",
    "    return s * (1 - s)\n",
    "\n",
    "def relu(z):\n",
    "    return np.maximum(0, z)\n",
    "\n",
    "def relu_deriv(z):\n",
    "    return np.where(z > 0, 1.0, 0.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Visualizing Functions & Derivatives"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "z = np.linspace(-5, 5, 200)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Sigmoid plot\n",
    "axes[0].plot(z, sigmoid(z), label='Sigmoid', color='blue', lw=2)\n",
    "axes[0].plot(z, sigmoid_deriv(z), label=\"Sigmoid Derivative\", color='cyan', linestyle='--')\n",
    "axes[0].set_title(\"Sigmoid and its Derivative\")\n",
    "axes[0].grid(True)\n",
    "axes[0].legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "# ReLU plot\n",
    "axes[1].plot(z, relu(z), label='ReLU', color='green', lw=2)\n",
    "axes[1].plot(z, relu_deriv(z), label=\"ReLU Derivative\", color='lime', linestyle='--')\n",
    "axes[1].set_title(\"ReLU and its Derivative\")\n",
    "axes[1].grid(True)\n",
    "axes[1].legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Exercises & Solutions\n",
    "\n",
    "### Exercise 1:\n",
    "Implement the **Swish** activation function ($f(z) = z \\cdot \\sigma(z)$) and compute its derivative by hand. Write the code for both below.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Solution:\n",
    "The derivative is:\n",
    "$$f'(z) = \\sigma(z) + z \\cdot \\sigma(z)(1 - \\sigma(z)) = f(z) + \\sigma(z)(1 - f(z))$$"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def swish(z):\n",
    "    return z * sigmoid(z)\n",
    "\n",
    "def swish_deriv(z):\n",
    "    s = sigmoid(z)\n",
    "    return s + z * s * (1 - s)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Test implementation\n",
    "print(\"Swish output at z=1.0:\", swish(1.0))\n",
    "print(\"Swish derivative output at z=1.0:\", swish_deriv(1.0))"
   ]
  }
